Definition: A soil type  is a taxonomic unit in soil science.
Soil, commonly referred to as dirt, or earth, is a mixture of organic matter, minerals, gases, liquids, and organisms that together support life  of plants and soil organisms.
Biodiversity or biological diversity is the variety and variability of life on Earth.
Fish farming or pisciculture involves commercial breeding of fish, most often for food, in fish tanks or artificial enclosures such as fish ponds.
Urban agriculture, urban farming, or urban gardening is the practice of cultivating, processing, and distributing food in or around urban areas.
Vertical farming is the practice of growing crops in vertically stacked layers.

Water is an inorganic compound with the chemical formula H2O. It is a transparent, tasteless, odorless, and nearly colorless chemical substance, and it is the main constituent of Earth's hydrosphere and the fluids of all known living organisms (in which it acts as a solvent).
Food is any substance consumed by an organism for nutritional support.
In agriculture, the yield is a measurement of the amount of a crop grown, or product such as wool, meat or milk produced, per unit area of land.
In economics, demand is the quantity of a good that consumers are willing and able to purchase at various prices during a given time.
Proteins are large biomolecules and macromolecules that comprise one or more long chains of amino acid residues.
Productivity is the efficiency of production of goods or services expressed by some measure.
Genetically modified crops (GM crops) are plants used in agriculture, the DNA of which has been modified using genetic engineering methods.
Greenhouse gas emissions from human activities strengthen the greenhouse effect, contributing to climate change.
Nitrogen is the chemical element with the symbol N and atomic number 7.
Breeding is sexual reproduction that produces offspring, usually animals or plants.
Livestock are the domesticated animals raised in an agricultural setting to provide labor and produce diversified products for consumption such as meat, eggs, milk, fur, leather, and wool.
Soil fertility refers to the ability of soil to sustain agricultural plant growth, i.e.
Potassium is the chemical element with the symbol K (from Neo-Latin kalium) and atomic number 19.
Agriculture encompasses crop and livestock production, aquaculture, fisheries and forestry for food and non-food products.
Manure is organic matter that is used as organic fertilizer in agriculture.

Agricultural biotechnology, also known as agritech, is an area of agricultural science involving the use of scientific tools and techniques, including genetic engineering, molecular markers, molecular diagnostics, vaccines, and tissue culture, to modify living organisms: plants, animals, and microorganisms.
Agricultural economics is an applied field of economics concerned with the application of economic theory in optimizing the production and distribution of food and fiber products.

Drip irrigation or trickle irrigation is a type of micro-irrigation system that has the potential to save water and nutrients by allowing water to drip slowly to the roots of plants, either from above the soil surface or buried below the surface.
Efficiency is the often measurable ability to avoid wasting materials, energy, efforts, money, and time while performing a task.

Aquaculture (less commonly spelled aquiculture), also known as aquafarming, is the controlled cultivation ("farming") of aquatic organisms such as fish, crustaceans, mollusks, algae and other organisms of value such as aquatic plants (e.g.
Animal nutrition focuses on the dietary nutrients needs of animals, primarily those in agriculture and food production, but also in zoos, aquariums, and wildlife management.
Animal welfare is the well-being of non-human animals.
In microeconomics, supply and demand is an economic model of price determination in a market.
Crop rotation is the practice of growing a series of different types of crops in the same area across a sequence of growing seasons.
Disease resistance is the ability to prevent or reduce the presence of diseases in otherwise susceptible hosts.
Compost is a mixture of ingredients used as plant fertilizer and to improve soil's physical, chemical, and biological properties.
Sustainable agriculture is farming in sustainable ways meeting society's present food and textile needs, without compromising the ability for current or future generations to meet their needs.
Soil health is a state of a soil meeting its range of ecosystem functions as appropriate to its environment.
Water resources are natural resources of water that are potentially useful for humans, for example as a source of drinking water supply or irrigation water.

Organic farming, also known as ecological farming or biological farming, is an agricultural system that uses fertilizers of organic origin such as compost manure, green manure, and bone meal and places emphasis on techniques such as crop rotation and companion planting.
Climate is the long-term weather pattern in a region, typically averaged over 30 years.
Poultry () are domesticated birds kept by humans for the purpose of harvesting useful animal products such as meat, eggs or feathers, and the practice of raising poultry is known as poultry farming.
Research is "creative and systematic work undertaken to increase the stock of knowledge".
Fiber or fibre (from Latin: fibra) is a natural or artificial substance that is significantly longer than it is wide.
In Modern English, they is a third-person pronoun relating to a grammatical subject.
Genetics is the study of genes, genetic variation, and heredity in organisms.
In its most general sense, the term "world" refers to the totality of entities, to the whole of reality or to everything that is.

Irrigation (also referred to as watering) is the practice of applying controlled amounts of water to land to help grow crops, landscape plants, and lawns.
Cattle (Bos taurus) are large, domesticated, cloven-hooved herbivores.
Bone meal is a mixture of finely and coarsely ground animal bones and slaughter-house waste products.
Deforestation or forest clearance is the removal of a forest or stand of trees from land that is then converted to non-forest use.
Land, also known as dry land, ground, or earth, is the solid terrestrial surface of Earth not submerged by the ocean or another body of water.

Selective breeding (also called artificial selection) is the process by which humans use animal breeding and plant breeding to selectively develop particular phenotypic traits (characteristics) by choosing which typically animal or plant males and females will sexually reproduce and have offspring together.
Food security speaks to the availability of food in a country (or geography) and the ability of individuals within that country (geography) to access, afford, and source adequate foodstuffs.
Management (or managing) is the administration of organizations, whether they are a business, a nonprofit organization, or a government body.
Genetic engineering, also called genetic modification or genetic manipulation, is the modification and  manipulation of an organism's genes using technology.
Population is the term typically used to refer to the number of people in a single area.
Technology is the application of knowledge for achieving practical goals in a reproducible way.
A fuel is any material that can be made to react with other substances so that it releases energy as thermal energy or to be used for work.
Animal husbandry is the branch of agriculture concerned with animals that are raised for meat, fibre, milk, or other products.
Phosphorus is a chemical element with the symbol P and atomic number 15.
Milk is a white liquid food produced by the mammary glands of mammals.
Meat is animal flesh that is eaten as food.
